SIMPLE: manifest
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manifest
<hw>Man"i*fest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>manifeste</ets>, L. <ets>manifestus</ets>, lit., struck by the
hand, hence, palpable; <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>fendere</ets> (in
comp.) to strike. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Defend</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Evident to the senses, esp. to the sight; apparent;
distinctly perceived; hence, obvious to the understanding; apparent to
the mind; easily apprehensible; plain; not obscure or hidden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither is there any creature that is not <qex>manifest</qex> in
his sight.</q> <rj><qau> Heb. iv. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which may be known of God is <qex>manifest</qex> in them.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. i. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus <qex>manifest</qex> to sight the god appeared.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Detected; convicted; -- with <ptcl>of</ptcl>.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Calistho there stood <qex>manifest</qex> of shame.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Open; clear; apparent; evident; visible;
conspicuous; plain; obvious.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Manifest</er>,
<er>Clear</er>, <er>Plain</er>, <er>Obvious</er>, <er>Evident</er>. What
is <xex>clear</xex> can be seen readily; what is <xex>obvious</xex> lies
directly in our way, and necessarily arrests our attention; what is
<xex>evident</xex> is seen so clearly as to remove doubt; what is
<ex>manifest</ex> is very distinctly evident.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>clear</qex>, so shining, and so <qex>evident</qex>,⟦br⟧
That it will glimmer through a blind man's eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Entertained with solitude,⟦br⟧
Where <qex>obvious</qex> duty erewhile appeared unsought.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I saw, I saw him <qex>manifest</qex> in view,⟦br⟧
His voice, his figure, and his gesture knew.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Manifest
<hw>Man"i*fest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Manifests</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>manifeste</ets>. See <er>Manifest</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Manifesto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A public declaration; an
open statement; a manifesto. See <er>Manifesto</er>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A list or invoice of a ship's cargo, containing a
description by marks, numbers, etc., of each package of goods, to be
exhibited at the customhouse; <as>as, to inspect the ship's
<ex>manifest</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Manifest
<hw>Man"i*fest</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Manifested</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Manifesting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To show plainly;
to make to appear distinctly, -- usually to the mind; to put beyond
question or doubt; to display; to exhibit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is nothing hid which shall not be <qex>manifested</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark iv. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy life did <qex>manifest</qex> thou lovedst me not.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exhibit the manifests or prepared invoices of; to
declare at the customhouse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reveal; declare; evince; make known; disclose;
discover; display.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifestable</ent>⟦br⟧
